icals, detective novels, science-fiction, and comic-books, is underpinned by the idea that the chess-player is a pluralistic subject used to articulate a number of anxieties pertaining to themes of mind, machine, and monster.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChess playersxSocial aspectsxHistory. 7aNON-CLASSIFIABLE.2bisacsh  aanimal.  aautomaton chess-player.  achild prodigy.  adetective fiction.  amasculinities.  amelancholic.  amonstrosity.  amonstrous bodies.  amoralities.  asinner.  astatuesque chess-player.  asuperhero.  atranshuman.1 aSharples, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612054040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526120540423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526120540/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles